description: The wide cyclable bus lane that comes all the way from Springvale Rd ends here, forcing cyclists into traffic for 3 major intersections before starting again after Elgar Rd.

There is no safe way to exit the bike path at this intersection. You're forced to leave the curb when it is busy with MCG fans. I have a horrible facial injury from the hidden grid which is off the curb.
When riding towards Geelong CBD, the lane suddenly tops after the bridge. There is no safe was to re-enter the traffic along with cars.

Cars and Bikes share the road until 100m before the roundabout.  A short bike lane starts approx 100m for (say) 70m.  ie No sharing the road.  Then the biCycle lane ends, road Narrows with bike sharrows.  Only a very brave or stupid cyclist would move into the lane.  It's uphill in this location.  Cyclists are going slowly.

spot_name: Box Hill to Ringwood Rail Trail,  Victoria
description: I have to get off and walk thru Box Hill Central to get to Thurston on the otherside where I can get on my bike again to ride to the city
Cycle lane converges into traffic roundabout with high traffic congestion.
South > North bike lane ends abruptly, need to merge with two lanes of heavy traffic.
The bike lane disappears into a turn left lane for cars, leaving no space for cyclists wishing to keep straight. Very dangerous intersection

spot_name: Federation Trail - Old Geelong Road Crossover
description: There is expectations that major trails have clear planned and developed routes.  At this location the Trail virtually ends at intersection. Riders need to cross 4 intersections with lights, before reach the next section of the trail.  This intersection has long Light Change sequences.  Waiting over 10min to get across. Riders try to cross without lights - dangerous due to poor Design.

If you cycle the Werribee or Federation Trails - they effectively end at this point and turn into a rough gravel track with no signage. There is a great concrete track on the West side of river, but need to carry your road bike down to the river and under the bridge.  Only a track for MTB‚Äùs.  Time to extend the Federation Trail.

The Southbank Boulevard cycle lanes are a great idea, but poorly executed (see the numerous comments already regarding intersections).
In addition, if the aim is to get cyclist off the Southbank promenade, then will need to give priority to bikes through the traffic lights (so you are able to ride the entire length with green lights - say at 18kmh).  Otherwise, rider will just stay on Southbank.

Time to extend the Bay Tail through Point Cook and Werribee South. There is a gravel track 20m from the end of trail, but in the Costal Park reserve.  Come on!!! It cannot be that hard to use this existing track rather than re-route the Trail.
comment_1: Charles Mellish: Agree, I commute from Saltwater Coast and it would reduce cycle time yo and from city by 10 minutes each way and reduces distance by about 10km. It would be greatly appreciated.
comment_2: Eugene Hobbs: Wyndham council lists a path through Sanctuary Lakes as a bike path. Yet it is listed along the footpath in front of houses with the potential for kids to run out.  The path is frequented by Sanctuary Lakes vehicles, registered, unregistered, lawnmowers plus golf buggies, and invariably blocked with builders vehicles, the only option is to ride on the single lane road

description: the service road ends and you are forced to ride out into 6 lane highway, between left turn lane and straight ahead to lane to continue into city bound lane
forced out into main highway

The exit from the roundabout into Peel St is at a right angle. The bike lane markings end just at that corner, and then begins again 10 metres after. Left turning traffic cuts across this corner, leaving no space for riders. I usually merge into the traffic lane well before but for this I cop a lot of anger from drivers. See photo below for the situation.
comment_1: Stefan: A solution to that could be a head start for bikes so they can safely pass this spot before any cars, or alternatively reduce the vehicle lane to just one lane and install a concrete barrier between bike path and actual road.
comment_2: Raymun: The bike lane resumes after the corner but then ends again as it approaches the intersection with Queensberry St. Furthermore, cars are often parked over the bike lane just prior to this intersection, forcing cyclists into traffic.

description: Riding south on Millers Rd approaching the round about the bike lane ends abruptly.  Trucks and Busses in the right next to bike lane and there is nowhere to go but on to footpath.  Is this the only way to travel though a roundabout now for cyclists????? Very disappointing and dangerous.

bike lane ends and tells cyclists to ride on footpath.  Footpath is too Narrow and has several lightpoles.  Pedestrians act negatively when there is a bike on the footpath which is fair enough to an extent. 
There should be a green painted bike lane so that cars are warned.

Each intersection on this road has bike lanes, and they disappear once past the intersection. The road is Narrow, and the drivers aggressive and impatient towards cyclists. This road is the main thoroughfare into, and around, Sunbury so hard to avoid of you ride for travel.
comment_1: Edwin Flynn: Totally agree about aggressive car drivers in SUNBURY. That is the reason I rarely ride my bike now.  I would love to ride often but drivers in SUNBURY are far too aggressive toward cyclists. Both physically intimidating buy driving far too close and fast and verbally intimidating as well.  I've had a chicken bone thrown from a utility . I struck me with some force as it drew blood where it hit me.  Fix driver attitudes and I may get back on my bike.

description: We have cycle lanes that disappear and is very busy intersection that a lot of car will not allow you to merge and drive up very close
The Wangoom Road training circuit is well signed to advise drivers but the bike lane is not continuous.
Major gap in between two good bike paths. Heave vehicle traffic.
Road Narrows

Signage is poor and it's unclear that you're going from a bike lane into an incredibly tight and congested traffic snarl here. Option to go onto the shared path to the east should be highlighted and a much wider ramp provided to do so (and one to get back onto the road at the front of the traffic to rejoin the road)
comment_1: Frank: Really should end the bike lane before the turn rather than do a 90 degree turn and have less than 5 Meters to stop or merge

description: Bike lane ends, and cars going straight ahead swing into the left lane without looking, to avoid right-turning cars.

There seems to be no safe way to get from Docklands & the Western Suburbs to South Melbourne by a reasonably direct route. There are ways of getting to & from the old CBD, but this is a gaping hole in safe cycle routes in inner Melbourne. The test is: would you allow your 13 y/o child to ride this (when they have to get off the footpath)?
This could be opened to cyclists to encourage people to cycle
Busy road no bike lane
comment_1: Linda: It is Ryrie Street not Linda Adams

description: Unsafe because bike lane become lane for cars

Very unclear how to navigate as a cyclist, needs more road markings and signage targeted for cyclists

For example going from Elizabeth St to Flemington Rd: if you follow the bicycle lane you are just taken off the roundabout to Peel St (or have to wait to try to cross two lanes of cars exiting Peel St to get back into the roundabout?); I've found it easier just to take the left-most traffic lane.
Need to formalize the link from the end of the Rail Trial at Osborne St to Belvoir Lagoon (Sumsion Gardens) trails. Osborne street and High st are too busy and Narrow, Huon st is a safer option.

When using the service road instead of cycling on the 80kmh main road cyclists must go back onto the main road at multiple locations to reach the next service road. It would not take much to pave very short sections to create crossings so that cyclists would not have to ride on the main road.

When using the service road instead of cycling on the 80kmh main road cyclists must go back onto the main road at multiple locations to reach the next service road. It would not take much to pave very short sections to create crossings so that cyclists would not have to ride on the main road.

When using the service road instead of cycling on the 80kmh main road cyclists must go back onto the main road at multiple locations to reach the next service road. It would not take much to pave very short sections to create crossings so that cyclists would not have to ride on the main road.

There is a shared path west of Diamond Creek and a good bridge across the creek but there is no (legal) provision for cyclists from the bridge to Main Road. The footpath should be widened and designated as shared to provide safe access.
path just ends at the corner trafic lights are up the road abit and dont line up with the bike path, its just not verry nice
intersection is pretty messy and the bike lane just ends when we need it most, really unsafe but i need to go thrugh it to get to work

Despite a designated space at the opposite side of Ballarat Rd for a cyclist (to continue forward) there is no lane on arrival to the other side of Gordon St. When a car takes the 2nd and furthest left lane coming from the same direction, upon reaching the other side of Ballarat Rd as the cyclist I only have my body width between the curb and that car in the left lane which feels very dangerous.

The trail is dumped on to a section of road for roughly 50 meters but the road is badly potholed and Narrow, with users of the oval not expecting bikes. The road should be Narrowed and a dedicated trail formed.
Eastbound BiCycle lane ends at a speedhump and road Narrowing point. Vehicles speed up trying to get in front of cyclists at the point where the road Narrows.
Cycle lane ends and cyclist mix with turning traffic.
Glenard Dr and Mt Eagle Rd are a good alternative to SR44 to the roundabout at Burke Road but the connection between them is barely usable on bike.
A good bike lane comes to an end.
Good bike lane on south side of Wellington Rd changes into Narrow footpath

There is a great off-road trail into the town of Milawa, from Wangaratta. But this stops and doesn't connect the 800m down to the biggest drawcard in the area - Brown Brothers Winery.  Cyclists then have to mix with road traffic, including many B-doubles.

Bike path connects onto one way road with no signage to say it is a one way road.
Bike path then continue‚Äôs at the other end of the road. 
Dangerous for young or inexperienced riders.

The excellent path built along the Dandenong Bypass just stops in the middle of nowhere. As does the road.
Why was this last section never built? It would make a massive difference.
comment_1: Colin: Why this wasn't linked up to the Eumemmerring Creek trail we'll never know.. somebody else's job I suppose. Such a lost opportunity.

description: It is very difficult to cross the road here, both for bicycles and pedestrians, to get to the shared path and footpath on the other side to cross the bridge.

spot_name: East Boundary Road - northbound towards North Road,  Victoria
description: Cycle lane ends just before a long left-turning lane ahead of a major intersection. When riding along the cycle lane, suddenly there is nowhere to go. Most of the time there is Too much vehicle traffic travelling too quickly to merge into the lane for traffic going straight ahead.
Land end and car get very close
Bike lane inexplicably ends.
The bike lane ends at the roundabout, making the merge into the traffic unsafe.

Mathoura Road is part of a bicycle route, and when accessing it from Toorak Road, the right turn is across two lanes of traffic including trams. Particularly difficult in the afternoon when traffic is bad in the outbound lanes, and you have to merge across and then wait in the centre of Toorak road to turn
comment_1: Mathoura Road being part of a designated bike route is laughable. No bike lane, pot holes and uneven surfaces, cars driving past at unsafe speeds. This intersection is highly dangerous and i have had multiple near misses here.
comment_2: Stonnington Council hates cyclists.

description: Along with being a pinch point, there is no infrastructure for cyclists to turn right into Gibson Ave.
comment_1: Leaf: Turning right is tricky here.

description: There needs to be a protected right turn for cyclists turning from Macaulay into Rankins.
Due to the construction works and resultant poor sequencing of the lights for motorists it becomes quite unsafe for cyclists and pedestrians.
comment_1: Agreed it is poor! and you cannot see the bicycle green light until ~10m prior to the solid line, so if its red and you have pace its challenging to stop

description: Continuing from crossing Carlton Gardens to Gertrude street has no traffic signals available to cyclists. One has to guess when it is safe to enter the intersection to continue down Gertrude street. Alternative is to cross with pedestrians and then shift over, which results in a temporal conflict with trams which is *awkward*
comment_1: MK: Bikes queue up adjacent to the pedestrian crossing here (in front of the car gate which is usually closed). If there aren't pedestrians waiting you have to pedal up to the pedestrian bit and then come back to the place you want to cross as a cyclist. It'd be great if there was a separate button just for cyclists here.

description: Cyclists turning left from Elgin must wait during tunes when it is otherwise safe to turn left, but when released by traffic lights are immediately in conflict with pedestrians using the crossing!
comment_1: Turning right from Swanston into Elgin also sucks. Have to cross into the lanes of traffic after the bike lane disappears right before the intersection.

description: Nearly impossible and dangerous trying to cross here. Very poor connectivity to access bike path.

spot_name: Capital City Trail entrance from Canning St
description: There's a tree on the left that obscures your view of traffic on the Capital City Trail as you're entering from Canning Street.
Walking path and bike path meet lack of signage
comment_1: John Van: plus dog walkers, pram pushers and yummy mummy joggers in their pink runners - stay on the Beach Road, much safer.
comment_2: Dan: Would be much better if  there was a second bridge

description: Riding the streets along the Craigieburn line has become very popular in recent years as a commuting route. There's a laneway that connects to The Crescent that is difficult to access due to high kerbs along Maribyrnong Rd. The alternative is to cross at Bayview Terrace, but westbound traffic flies over the bridge to the right and makes is very dangerous, when riding north.
comment_1: Martin: A pram ramp here would be nice

description: Very poor visibility from turning cars who are allowed to share the crossing with bike lanes. Almost hit on a green light

Ever tried turning right into Commercial Road on a bike? A nightmare. There's a short concrete median that makes it very hard to turn when trying to access the back of Footscray Primary School. Also very unsafe because traffic heading west along Barkly are right up behind you, and as impatient as we know Melbourne drivers usually are.

Heading towards the city and want to turn right into Pilgrim St from Victoria St? Good luck using this pointless median crossing, which means riding against traffic to be able to access the left hand lane. An easy fix for the responsible authority.
Need to cross two lanes of traffic to reach bike lane
This intersection has poor visibility for driver and cyclists as well as being busy
comment_1: Emma: Dangerous, this is part of the northern bike trail coming off Park St. Many children and bikes turn here and there is a car run through on White St into Rae St creating a very dangerous intersection for bikes.

description: This intersection is totally dangerous for both bicycle and pedestrian it should be an underpass or an overpass. Solar power could provide a lift for walkers/cycles who can‚Äôt manage stairs.
Bikes have to cross over left turning traffic to get into the cycling lane to turn right

Echoing some other comments here, this intersection is an absolute death trap for cyclists.  The cycle lane just ends at the top of Elizabeth st, and unless you are turning down Peel st or onto Flemington Rd, its not safe to try to continue around onto Royal Parade. There needs to be clearer bike lanes and a staggered traffic light system here, I've had too many close calls with impatient drivers.
comment_1: Martin: The problem with "clearer bike lanes" would be that if they are on the outside of the roundabout, bikes using them would still have to give way at each exit (road rule 119).

description:
Dangerous to turn right onto Nepean from Inkerman to join bike path into city - no clear lane for cyclists 
- need to cross large intersection with limited time
- through traffic coming in opposite direction typically runs amber/red lights to 'make the lights' resulting in delay in turning right - often after the lights have changed.

Victoria Parade upgrade works were disastrous for cyclists. Gisbourne St lane northbound should have connected to Fitzroy St to provide a safe passage for cyclists to Brunswick St, to avoid the dangerous Brusnwick & Victoria intersection. Would be an easy adjustment for amazing benefit!

High speed roundabout with congested traffic and impatient drivers. Debris on the edges where cyclists would be riding. It's a large roundabout that will take time for a cyclist to get through. I do not ride it for these reasons

Entry to McKean St is blocked at Rushall Cr to cars, as it's a one way road to traffic. But cyclists use McKean all the time in both directions. At the roundabout, how about a concrete crossover for riders to get access to McKean, rather than having to ride up a Narrow one way section against traffic.
Dawson street is used largely by school kids going who are particularly vulnerable. Separated bike lanes are needed and improved crossing arrangements for bicycles are needed.
This intersection is used by kids going to school and has inadequate protections for crossing. Part of the suggested bike route
comment_1: Alan: Many cars making illegal right turns into Garnett St from Moreland Road

description: Bike path crosses road between light rail crossing and roundabout. Really dangerous as it‚Äôs not obvious to cars that a bike path crosses the road. Should have high vis paint like other intersections. I‚Äôve seen numerous near misses
comment_1: Belinda: Very dangerous- agree
comment_2: Skeg: Yes - wrote to Port Phillip council about this one. Sometimes you can get long runs of vehicles flying through here doing the rat run from Willy Road. I suggested they put in a pedestrian crossing - signed only - weren't interested. Pretty pathetic response considering a few signs and lines would cost stuff all.

spot_name: Wingrove Street/Yarana - darabin Crk trail,  Victoria
description:
Arrangement @Yarana/Wingrove junction with Darebin crk trail poor&creates vehicle conflict.Travelling east on Wingrove,to turn North @DCT,one signals Left, then passes southbound cars@Wingrove stop line,cars expect riders to have turned up Yarana and commence to pull out. Requiring evasive braking.
To make intended crossover&bollard gaps @ Traffic speed requires wide line. Many'd rather shortcut.
comment_1: Andrew: I agree this is a potentially dangerous & difficult spot. When approaching this intersection from the west (on the road) and intending to turn left onto the bike path, I don't know whether to indicate left or not - I don't want a car waiting at the intersection to assume I'll turn up the road and pull out in front of me, and I need to have both hands on the handlebars to navigate the zig-zags and bumps to get onto the bike path
comment_2: Why not just ride up Yarana and join DCT at the end of the street (at Parklands Ave) like almost everyone else?
comment_3: Cam: They made that more difficult by removing the straight path at Parklands Ave, still better to ride across the now garden bed instead of using this entrance to the trail here.

description: Difficult for cars to see cyclists as the approaching. Would be good for street marking to say look out for cyclists

Bike lane traffic light stays green while cars coming down In st.georges towards city at 70 km/h can Left turn in to Oakover road, cars have to completely stop in green to turn if there is a on coming bike, which makes it unsafe for bikes and cars
comment_1:
Martin: Had a car on car rear end crash happen here a few years ago due to the above, although that was before they changed the rules on giving way at signalized bike crossings.

I tend to use High St or ride on the road here to avoid this section (Showers to Miller St), though other parts of the St Georges Rd path are quite good IMO.

description: This is a large roundabout with a lot of traffic in the morning. It is quite difficult and risky to make a right turn from Fitzsimons Lane into Porter Street.
comment_1: Don Macrae: I regularly ride through this intersection on Porter Street. It is frightening because of the speed at which traffic drives through it, and because there is no safe path for cyclists. Outbound is particularly bad because the right lane can either turn left or proceed straight, so we need to get between the lanes and be aware of all possibilities

description: This intersection has a lot of traffic for such a Narrow road and the light cycle is too short for a clearing in the traffic to turn the corner
comment_1: Gravityandme: Feel unsafe in general around melbourne when there is no proper bike path

description: This crossing has poor lines of sight. Although it is a pedestrian crossing I have frequently had cars not see me and drive through
comment_1: JCP: Drivers seem to deliberately ignore the pedestrian signage here and race through this crossing. Have had personal close calls here.

description: Cars turning west onto high st from harp rd frequently fail to give way. The intersection has poor visibility, with sun often in drivers' eyes. I am always cautious here

spot_name: Chandler Highway crossing from east to west
description: I have been hit here. There is no room on road to cross as a cyclist wishing to travel north on Chandler so you have to use the pedestrian crossing which is frequently blocked by cars. The whole connection from the Anniversary trail to Chandler needs to be fixed
Some drivers don‚Äôt check for cyclists there and some just ignore them when they actually see them.
comment_1: yes, coming down Maidston is the car's thoroughfare but traffic from Apex park has right of way and that is where the cyclist are coming from.

description: Nightmarish spot. Cars always blocking the bike lane or turning across the bike lane with no respect for cyclists.
comment_1: Heather: Especially when doing a right turn from Toorak Road West. We need a bicycle traffic light to give us a head start.

description: As a cyclist no easy way to get from at Kilda Rd into Barkly or fitroy st. Almost better to ride few extra kms and go via Port Melbourne bike path, Beaconsfield bike path. To st Kilda.

spot_name: Kirby, Burke and Doncaster Road Junction ,  Victoria
description: Heading west from Doncaster Rd to Kirby Rd have to effectively turn right across tram tracks going down an incline. There is no turn lane and it is dangerous to wait in the right lane with through traffic and trams.

Betweeen the trams, the traffic lights further down, and the intersection, I‚Äôve seen a few accidents here. A mother cycle ride, and bike rider get hit. It‚Äôs really dangerous spot to cross especially on a bike.
comment_1: Ryan: Cars should not be allowed to drive across here so many times I've seen cars speed in front of cyclists cause they see a gap in traffic but don't actually look. Either move the lights or put an island in the middle to stop cars speeding through.
comment_2: Melanie: Agreed! I feel uneasy both when riding along St George‚Äôs Rd, or crossing over between Reid St and Alfred Crescent. Moving the lights would make a huge difference.
comment_3: Louise: Agreed with comments above
comment_4: 100 pct agree. Cars routinely 'shoot' across here, Narrowly missing bikes and cars alike. Also, on northbound traffic, I find the cars often poke out their nose into the bike lane when that light turns red. It's super dangerous because often cars will try to speed up the inside and beat other cars
comment_5: This intersection needs a rethink - unsafe for pedestrians crossing to Ed Gardens, cyclists and not safe for cars either. Close to a primary school and library should be a priority.

description: The two joined roundabouts makes it unclear for both drivers and cyclist where they are going. Often leads to dangerous situations when intent is misunderstood.
comment_1:
David Gordon: It is common for vehicles entering the Beach Rd roundabout from the Balcombe Rd roundabout to fail to give way to bike riders entering the Beach Rd roundabout from the north. 
I have experienced numerous near collisions caused by poor driver courtesy or driver error when their vehicle enters the Beach Rd roundabout in my path when I am riding my bike and have right of way.

description: Cars coming up Baden Powell Dr and turning right onto Tangenong often indicate very late. This creates a dangerous for bicycles coming down Baden Powell Dr which has to stop for them at the roundabout.

Travelling west along the Heathmont rail trial the pth terminates at Canterbury rd. You have to cross at the pedestrian lights, ride past the station and then cross the rail way line at a Narrow, poorly designed crossing before picking up the trail again on the other side. This connection needs to be fixed and signage improved
comment_1: Arthur: I have always crossed Canterbury Rd and then rode across the rail bridge and then left onto the trail along the station, but signage might possibly need improving.

description: It is difficult to turn right in to  Grand Blvd from Bolton st if you are on road. There have been significant improvements here but a wider shoulder on the right for bikes turning right could help
Dangerous location to cross the road and tram tracks to access the bike path through the park. Vehicles won't provide right of way.

spot_name: Glen Huntly Road and Nepean Intersection
description: Very long intersection, many vehicles moving fast, with no marked lanes, together with many tram tracks.

Insane design that was known to be terrible from day 1. It's time to fix these lanes around the back of tram stops which are strewn with gravel or sand, very bumpy, have to give way to side street traffic and have no safe sightlines so you basically have to stop.

Insane design that was known to be terrible from day 1. It's time to fix these lanes around the back of tram stops which are strewn with gravel or sand, very bumpy, have to give way to side street traffic and have no safe sightlines so you basically have to stop.

Cars parked all up the road (unsafe for possible car dooring), bike lane is too Narrow because traffic builds in two lanes. To go straight you need to force your way into the middle of the road in heavy traffic as most is left turning and no room
Hiatus in cyclist options at this major nexus heading south from Main Yarra Trail; too many cars in multiple directions during non-virus times.

spot_name: Capital City Trail / Main Yarra Trail, Melbourne Victoria
description: Have seen bike/bike collisions here. Signage isn't clear who has a right of way.
comment_1: Four way cycle and pedestrian traffic plus bollards to thread between, very dangerous.

description: Warburton Trail crosses Old Gippsland Rd on a corner with a blind spot looking down the hill. Also, there is little warning when cars turn into Old Gippsland Rd from Queen/Old Gippsland Rd intersection.
comment_1: Pete: Yes, I find this a quite disturbing crossing. No visibility at all when heading towards Mt Evelyn and the drivers often speed through showing callous disregard for trail users.

description: The traffic on Sebire Ave from Seville approaches the Warburton Rail Trail around a blind corner which does not give cyclists and walkers much time to react. There is a small traffic island in the middle of the road but driver visibility is poor until almost upon the intersection.

spot_name: Creswick Road and Macarthur st Intersection
description: There is too much vehicle  traffic and no safe way for cyclists to cross the dangerous intersection.
cars cut left cross cycle lane at speed and without looking

spot_name: Vehicle crossover of St Georges Road Trail,  Victoria
description: Poorly designed/signed cross-over of bike path, vehicles frequently cross without looking/giving way and sit across bike lane, blocking bike traffic

Regularly when trying to cross entry into Knox City Shopping Centre & heading north up Stud Road, cars turning off Stud Road into Knox City appear to go through a red light. This may be 1-3 cars at a time and it happens regularly that you have a "green man" and cars are still turning into your path.

spot_name: Half arsed lane marking across intersection, St Georges Road Trail,  Victoria
description: In addition to the other comments re: the bus stop overlapping the bike/ped crossing, and the Arthurton road vehicles turning right onto St Georges always getting stuck and blocking the bike lane... the actual line-up of the bike lane paintwork on the road with the actual bike path is completely unaligned. What's painted on the road does not meet up with entry/exit of bike lanes! You had 1 thing!

spot_name: Crappy new vehicle cross-over St Georges Road Trail,  Victoria
description:
Poorly designed/signed cross-over of bike path, vehicles frequently cross without looking/giving way and sit across bike lane, blocking bike traffic. The whole design of the cross-over favours vehicle safety/priority, not path users.
South-bound bikes travelling fast down the hill.
comment_1: Martin: The minor crossovers have stop signs and priority to the path, but there's not a lot of room for error or to know if someone is stopping, so you have to slow down or veer across the far side of the path anyway.

spot_name: Another crappy vehicle crossover, St Georges Road Trail,  Victoria
description: Poorly designed/signed cross-over of bike path, vehicles frequently cross without looking/giving way and sit across bike lane, blocking bike traffic. The whole design of the cross-over favours vehicle safety/priority, not path users. Larger vehicles - trucks, vehicles with trailers - completely block the path
comment_1: Ingrid Wilkinson : This is a great spot to see inner city hipsters with big bushy beards holding their cup of tea ride their unicycle down a leafy concrete jungle. In general this median strip is filthy.

spot_name: Roslyn Road & Thornhill Road, Highton Victoria
description: Cars turning and impatient as the T intersection is busy. School down the road and road is now used as an alternative to Barrabool Road and to Deakin Uni via Thornhill Road.

spot_name: Elgar Park Entrance Elgar Road,  Victoria
description: This should crossing should give priority to human power rather the turning motorised power which is hard to see given the angle the northnound bike rider approaches it

Not enough room to legally and safely stop in front of the pedestrian crossing when making a hook turn from Power St southbound into Burwood Rd westbound. Please move the crossing and stop line back from the intersection to create enough room for this without getting run over by southbound through traffic in the left lane
Not an intersection, but very sharp corner with poor quality surface (tree roots, pebbles...). Please ring your bell to communicate your presence to other people riding the opposite direction.
No cycle lanes at convergence of two roundabouts and a rail crossing.
comment_1: Sarah: Agree, I avoid if possible

description: From this point, to cross the highway to the other side (McLeod St) is absolutely terrible. There is no signage, there are obstacles in the way, some parts are extremely Narrow, and any mistake could lead the cyclists to a very dangerous situation, such as unknowingly ride on the highway access ramp. Everything that could go wrong with this intersection has.
Onstreet parking blocks sight lines when trying to cross the intersection to rejoin the St Georges Path which means you have to creep out to see, speeding vehicles makes this quite dangerous.
Unsafe surface can lead to wheel slip- particularly dangerous as often will be in middle of peloton here. very busy cycling section
Have been clipped by a car here travelling straight on Wellington Parade while I was indicating right to head to Bridge Road.

Turning left from Poplar Rd onto the CCT is dangerous as there is a lamp post right in the middle of it. How could that happen? If the ramp onto the pavement could be widened that issue could be avoided.

Cars turning into Racecourse Rd from Bellair St have poor visibility of cyclists travelling westwards on the Narrow bike lane. Although there is a stop sign, drivers edge in to the cycle lane and cyclists then have to swerve/emergency merge into traffic.
This intersection is ridiculous. Drivers speed and inappropriately merge and leave cyclists completely exposed
Steep hill with high speed downhill intersection for the cyclist. I avoid riding uphill and take a detour.

Roads crossing the Capital City trail in adjacent streets prioritise cyclists and pedestrians but Rae St and Brunswick St Nth crossings prioritise cars. The inconsistency catches out some drivers, cyclists and pedestrians causing some near misses.

Dangerous merge with the Narrowing lanes, and many cars trying to veer off to the left down Smith St. I suggest sharrows clearly showing that bikes will be in the lane, as it's not wide enough for a proper bike lane and would be unsafe anyway
No bike lanes, feels dangerous especially cross upper heidelberg from seddon onto livingstone st
Very tight car lanes, no bike lane, dangerous intersection
Cyclists should get right of way crossing the road.
Cyclists should get right of way crossing the road.
City trail should be given longer crossing time and increased frequency of green light to allow safe crossing and reduce build up of path users.
City trail should be given longer crossing time and increased frequency of green light to allow safe crossing and reduce build up of path users.

description: Narrow roads put drivers in the bike lane too often

spot_name: Beach Rd and Charman Road,  Beaumaris, Victoria
description:
The road Narrows, the bike lane Narrows, it‚Äôs at an intersection, and it‚Äôs on a bend.
There is lots of space to widen the road and bike lane.
comment_1: Su: I cycle and run in this area 2-3 times a week. I have seen drivers exiting Charman Rd (travelling north to south) to turn west onto Beach Road (towards Cliff Gve) swerve into the cycle lane and have 'near misses' with cyclists in the lane. Really bad drivers do this with excessive speed. They don't care if their vehicle needs a larger turning arc because of their speed. Being in the bike lane riding east to west on Beach Road when a driver from Charman wants to turn onto Beach road in the same direction you're pedalling is hairy. Drivers aren't looking at cyclists in the bike lane coming from the east. They're looking at traffic from the west. When they shoot across 2 lanes of traffic with speed, they don't realise how their vehicle swings into the bike lane. Regular riders should have Cycliq/dashcam footage of this. Sorry I don't.
comment_2:
David Gordon: I frequently ride through this intersection too, between 3 and 6 times a week. There are dangers for Beach Rd bike riders travelling west-east and east-west.
My perception is that dangers are much worse when riding west-east. This is by far the most dangerous point for bike riders on the Beach Rd training route between St Kilda and Mordialloc. The road Narrows on approach to the Charman Rd intersection, motor traffic is hemmed in by a concrete median strip, and the painted bike lane Narrows as well. 
It is common when passing through here to find vehicles parallel parked beside the kerb. The parked vehicles force riders into conflict with passing motor vehicles travelling west-east. Some passing vehicles wish to turn left into Charman Rd and pass dangerously close to the front wheel of bike riders instead of waiting behind the bike rider to execute their turn.
Cars turning right into Beach Rd from Charman Rd frequently fail to give way to bike riders and other traffic travelling west-east.
If car parking was prohibited on Beach Rd 150m either side of this intersection it would be much safer for bike riders.
When riding east-west I have had fewer unfavourable interactions with motor vehicles. I have not witnessed terrifying incidents where vehicles turning right into Beach Rd from Charman at high speed that the comment above describes but it is not difficult to imagine. 
My worst experiences at this intersection when riding east-west occur when passing slower riders or riding two abreast in the Narrow painted bike lane. When doing so it is common to receive aggressive treatment (horn blaring, dangerously close overtaking or swooping) from passing motorists.
Experienced riders brace themselves when passing through this intersection. For inexperienced cyclists riding through the Charman Rd intersection would be terrifying. Passing though here on a bike has been a nasty experience for many years. Modification of the intersection to make it safer for bike riders is long overdue. 
However, one safety change has already made a big difference at this intersection. Before trucks were banned from Beach Rd just about every time I rode through here west-east I suffered frighteningly close interactions with trucks. It was uncanny. Why did trucks always pass me there? With most trucks now gone from Beach Rd I am scared witless much less frequently at Charman Rd. Thank you for banning trucks from Beach Rd!

description: Too Narrow makes it frightening. Not much can be done except remove parked cars from one side or direct cyclists to use Royal Avenue.

comment_1: David Hall: Forthcoming proposal to add separated bicycle lane to Mont Albert Rd will allow for some to ride west up the hill and others to safely dismount and walk up. It also addresses Rochester and Balwyn Rd intersections.

Has been reported never repaired

description: There is No bicycle lanes and on top of that, the road reduces it's width , so, Cars pass next ro the rider very very close, one day was soo close that it was less than 10 cms. Horrible experience.

description:

lane-markings are ambiguous making it difficult to navigate as traffic merges to avoid parked cars heading west

description: Transition to high speed road, lack of bike lane

comment_1:
Neil Wilson: I agree with previous comments, and would like to add:
- The recently sealed shoulder on the GAR through Porepunkah urgently needs repairs at two locations (they are a significant hazard to cyclists)

Busy Narrow road with no bike lanes.

3 lanes merge into one - cars don't look for bikes

On the most direct rout from North Melbourne to South Melbourne and surrounding a major public transport hub:

No cycling options. On road with heavy vehicles traveling ~80km/h
Peak hour morning and afternoon, heavy traffic no bike lanes and a Narrow road. Often stop and start with railway boom gates. Big risk of dooring

I live in Rutherglen & I‚Äôm very proud of the Murray to Mountains rail trail section we have (albeit repairs are needed to the surface) between Wahgunyah and Rutherglen. There is no rail trail linking our section to the Wangaratta to Bright M2M section. Locals and tourist visitors are forced to cycle on the Narrow shoulder of C376 or the C375. Connec the rail trail Rutherglen to Wang via springhur

This is a very busy road and it's very dangerous to walk or ride along with the amount and speed of cars. The side of the ride drops into a ditch almost immediately so there is little room for cyclists or walkers, many families feel unsafe walking on the road themselves let alone there children.

The lack of a cycle lane on Barkly St between Gordon and Geelong Rd, particularly at the Geelong Rd / Barkly St intersection which is huge and drivers are often aggressively trying to get through. This road has a very Poor surface and there are no bike lanes along here.
The road is the parked with cars on the side with only one lane for both cars and cyclists.

comment_1:
Max: There are plans for construction of an alternate trail along the south side of Burwood Highway.
https://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/planning-and-projects/melbourne-road-projects/burwood-highway-shared-use-path

description: no bike lanes
no bike lanes, high risk of doing
no bike lanes, and lots of people doing iligal u turns and opening doors at weird times
no bike lane, sharp bend
Bike lane disappears at the most busy intersection alomg mont albert rd

spot_name: Harris Gully Road, Warrandyte South Victoria
description: Once again, a popular bike route has absolutely no shoulder or safe space for cyclists. Heavy vehicle traffic moving at speed makes it a really unpleasant place to ride.

I use this route to avoid Harris Gully and it never fails that at least one driver will pass me too closely. There is more than enough space for a 1.5 meter shoulder in both directions which would remove most of the friction points. Once you cross the roundabout at Falconers Road, there seem to be fewer issues with driver behaviour.
Being one of the main east-west routes across the Mornington Peninsular, I am surprised that there is no cycleway along this road.
This road (Anderson's Road is sometimes popular with cyclists. Perhaps some signs warning of the presence of riders might make it a bit safer.

comment_1: Sarah K: Bike lanes here are a joke.

description: The centre lane with its combined straight/turning option leads to motorists trying to race cyclists in the left lane, to squeeze them out merging left to avoid someone waiting to turn right (or as the arrow goes red). The biCycle lane ends are cyclists are forced into oncoming traffic at the intersection
There's a space for the bike lane but no signage for it, so it's not a legal bike lane.

The entire Snow Road would be a remarkable cycling route with attractive destinations and links to the nearby rail trail. However with 100km/h traffic and no bike lane or off road track then most of it is far too dangerous for the average cyclist. The snow road is a cycling opportunity going begging.
comment_1: Ric: Well said.

description: This is a very busy car route and there are No bicycle lanes.  There are very wide footpaths that could accommodate a bike lane.  There is a bike route between Findon Crescent and Stevenson St.  This could be continuous with a bike lane that is off road on the footpath.

The new upgrade of Sisely Ave has made cycling more difficult along this section of road. Particularly on the southern side of Sisely Ave. It's a poor design which squeezes cyclists far too close to cars and the many trucks which use this section of road.

comment_1: no access for bikes from Hampton Park, Lynbrook, Cranbourne etc. Vic Roads told me there is a bike path all  the way along here, they have NO CLUE. There is not even a foot path.

description: Generally a quiet area but so many cars use this area to avoid traffic - they ‚Äúrat run‚Äù through the Cresent and Mercantile Pde (from Smithfield road or Kensington road) especially in morning peak which makes it unsafe as there‚Äôs no bike lanes and this corner gets especially busy, with bikes and people and cars coming from all directions. Need a way to stop the ‚Äúrat running‚Äù

The adjacent path is used by too many pedestrians and 100s of cyclists use this road to access the Dandenongs. Would be great to have a bike lane wide enough to support groups riding side by side here in both directions.

A disgrace.
No bike lane, no footpaths, no hard shoulder, high speed heavy traffic, and yet this is main access road to industrial estates and then residential suburbs.
comment_1: no access for bikes from Hampton Park, Lynbrook, Cranbourne etc. Vic Roads told me there is a bike path, they have NO CLUE

description: No room for cycles

spot_name: Gisborne - Melton Road, Toolern Vale Victoria
description: The road has a limit of 100km, single lane and is dangerous for bike riders and walkers as it is. Nearly taken out by a car due to no bike lane.  I was too shaky to continue riding well and felt it my responsibility to get off the road.  If you‚Äôre not drivers felt the same level of responsibility towards cyclists.

No bicycle lane on this road and public transportation (bus) that runs on this road is insufficient ‚Äî there is only one bus service and that bus service only runs on weekdays in the early mornings and late evenings. Safe bicycle path/lane needed or more frequent public transportation options required.

There is a bike lane on the Caulfield side of Dandenong Road on Kooyong Road but then it ends and there is nothing in Malvern.  Riding along Kooyong Road between Dandenong Road and Toorak Road without a bike lane is scary at times especially at the intersections

There is no bike lane on Glenferrie Road between Dandenong Road and the Main Yarra Trail bike track.  Riding along Glenferrie Road between Dandenong Road and the entry to the main Yarra trail (between Toorak Road and Riversdale Road) without a bike lane is scary at times especially at the intersections.  Also riding through the shops on Glenferrie Road without a bike lane dooring is an issue
there is not much room and lots of cars turning into side streets and drive ways
No bike lane. Wide lane for cars to park are blocked. Cars drive unsafely
No bicycle lanes and bicycle paths. Public transportation services are very limited!
Sydney Road is busy and there is little room for bike riders and cars in the area do not respect the right of bike riders to share the road safely. We need a separate bike lane.
Blind spot. Needs a mirror so see around a blind spot as one exists from under the bridge. A mirror was there once but has been removed!
The arch shape of the footbridge is too striking.

description: Narrow, swinging bridge
comment_1: Will: this bridge is not adequate for cyclists and pedestrians, the hairpin turn on the eastern side is also low visibility and dangerous
comment_2: Georgie : This bridge is unsafe on the eastern side as there is no visibility of anyone coming down the hill at the merge from the path. There is also not adequate room to dismount (as required) without stopping on a hill in a blind spot. The bridge itself is too Narrow for a person walking with a bike and another person to go past. comment_3: Eugene: Dog off lead blocked complete bridge, until the dog was called by the owner

description: Sharp blind corner is often cut by oncoming cycle and foot traffic. Have seen all ages cut this corner, and have had some very near collisions. Corner is blind due to high fence. Installed Slow signs help, but are often ignored. Recommend adding mirror.

spot_name: Federation Trail Skeleton Creek Trail,  Victoria

description: The lane markings have been changed over time and the old markings are still visible. Vehicles routinely drive along the bike lane following the old centre lane marking

description: Drivers turning left out of Carlton street onto Rathdowne st fail to see cyclists coming out of Barkly street. I was personally involved in a collision at this intersection.

spot_name: Cnr of Fenwick Street and Chadstone Road, Victoria
description: It's a pretty steep downhill and cars can jump out at you. Sometimes cars think they can quickly drive out as your coming down the road.

spot_name: Mt Albert rd Elgar rd intersection
description: Bikes do not trigger the traffic light if waiting on Mt Albert rd to travel east across Elgar rd towards the bike path near Box Hill pool
comment_1: David Hall: Forthcoming proposal for a separated cycle-way along Mont Albert Rd will upgrade that intersection for bikes.
comment_2: EdJ: Hope that will happen I use the BoxHill Ringwood trail regularly and then loop south towards Aqualink and up Standard Avenue. Heading west where Mont Albert meets Elgar there is a compulsory left turn signposted  and no straight on light sequence...I've always guessed that the alternative to illegally entering the cycle lane is dismounting and an extended wait as a pedestrian to cross two sections of road...very poor provision currently and not a lot of good alternative (if any) west heading cycling provision

description: Multiple blind corners on this stretch of path - especially westbound when speed tends to be higher

comment_1: Su: Having humans on the median strip between lanes of vehicle traffic is awful. A good friend and neighbour had an Uber driver travelling at 80km/h on Nepean Hwy looking at their phone. When red lights came up for drivers and green lights for pedestrians, my friend started walking but the driver failed to see the red lights. The driver eventually saw my friend walking on the green pedestrian signal and slammed on the brakes, skidding part way into the pedestrian crossing and forcing my friend to jump out the way. In addition or alternative to the suggestion above, how about some bridges for walkers and cyclists over the highway?

description: As an infrequent rider in this part of Melbourne, the wayfinding at this intersection is abysmal. A few signs would help, instead of being reliant on some previous cyclists painting directions on the path.

When the rain comes through, this area consistently floods the path - there is a drain that comes down and passes over the path. However, it brings a large amount of silt and soil across the path. Cones tend to be put out for a period then removed. A Poor Design Outcome. the concern here is cyclists track on a Narrow section in the silt to avoid running through it, increasing conflicts.
comment_1: John: Agree with the comments here
comment_2: Will: Agree

description: This connection isn't demonstrated well for cyclists and pedestrians. Poor lighting in the evening means this convenient connection to southern side of the Yarra is underutilized. A second crossing on the western side of the tracks would help connect Cremorne to South Yarra also.
another run off spot for silt. results in poor cyclist behaviour to avoid silt on path.
Improved signage required to indicate where trail resumes after road crossing
Bikes don't trigger the traffic lights so have to dismount and use the pedestrian crossing or wait for a car to use the intersection.
Once I had a car nearly reverse into me there because they started reversing into a parking spot suddenly. Then a truck drove partly in the bike lane too close. So I don't ride there anymore.

Why is the crossing light here red by default, forcing you to stop and wait ages for the light? The road isn't even open, and there's a red arrow on Chandler Hwy preventing turning here.

Northbound I just use the new bridge and Chandler Hwy instead because it's so much easier. I expect this will continue until I see it's changed!
The traffic lights do not register the weight of a bicycle and will not allow a right turn unless there is vehicle traffic also.

Most signs that pertain to us are painted on the footpath. My husband got a hefty fine here bc he didn‚Äôt see the signs. There ought to be painted signs on the road alerting cyclists.

The tram stop upgrade has done nothing to improve safety for bicycles. No bike lane combined with impatient drivers now having to change lanes every block or two lead to many very dangerous situations. comment_1: Tim Stoney: Could agree more, I get thee need for these new tram stops but they are a nightmare for cyclists, especially at night. Pedestrians edging out from footpath while cars try to squeeze past to beat trams. I had to avoid a pedestrian the other day and nearly got cleaned up by a car racing the tram - and of course I got blamed. Yelled at by pedestrian, horn blasted by motorist. You can win at these squeeze points and there are too many of them around Melbourne. Lanes just end and leave you hanging out there as cyclist.
comment_2: Tara: Agree
comment_3: Andrew: I also experienced a near miss at this trams stop with an impatient driver. This new style of tramstop solves one problem (accessibility) but creates another by increasing the potential for conflicts between cars, cyclists and pedestrians.

description: Getting from one side to the other safely on green light... It has got to be one of the most time stealing crossings in Melbourne.
comment_1: Cars continuously ignore the red right turn light, and the green pedestrian light, when turning right into College Crescent. Needs to be a stop signal for cars heading north, to allow bikes and pedestrians to cross safely. Bike traffic light signals may help.

description: At this intersection cyclists coming from Albert park  navigate cars travelling a round about, entering the school front entrance, And trams turning right

There are multiple reasons why it is unsafe, including inadequate shoulder in parts which is used in lieu of a bicycle lane, gravel obstructing the use of the shoulder in places, drivers failing to provide adequate clearance particularly where there are pinch points as well as bad driver behaviour with some drivers seeing cyclists on the road as targets.  This section of shoulder is very Narrow.
Merging traffic heading bearing left towards Heidi as road bears right towards Bulleen
Lots of unaware dog walkers with dogs off leash around this area; have Narrowly avoided crashing into dogs alone on the path, as well as dogs getting aggro at bikes going path. Not safe at all!

A lot of fast traffic and the road is barely 2 lanes wide. Steep hill where cyclists slow down and the traffic either banks up behind them or passes on double lines too close to the cyclist and too dangerous to pass.

spot_name: Entry/Exit form Western Ring Rd Trail to Blaxland Avenue,  Victoria
description: Entering the trail from Blaxland Ave is a Blind spot with cyclist's speeding done the ramp

The car park is dangerous for cyclists and pedestrians. (plenty of bike parking, mostly in the wrong place) In contrast, Central West has made good provision for pedestrians at least.

Needs signage to navigate cyclists coming from Beechworth / Everton onto the Markwood Tarrawingee Rd so they avoid riding down the Snow Rd to Milawa

This is a very popular route and the Snow Rd is a no go zone for cyclists.
Soon someone will be killed again.
Snakes alive! I rode over one in April. Be wary of snakes near the river trails come spring
VicRoads - incapable of learning from international best practice, destroying Melbourne with a car-only mindset for decades.
Dog-walkers. Dogs off-leash but allowed by owners to walk along the shared trail. Dogs in off-leash parks need to be kept well away from the path, and leashed when taken along the path.
Travelling East-West, this is a popular off-main road cycling route.  However it is difficult to cross brunswick st because of the often congested traffic and poor visibility.

lots of middle aged women. will take up the bike path and hurl verbal abuse to cyclists, really its just disappointing. 
also issues with them walking dogs across the whole path so you cant pass

Last time I tried, the northbound sensor doesn't detect my bike so I was waiting for a few cycles of lights until the car behind finally got close enough to activate it

Please let us contraflow on Flinders Lane for this section to detour around the tunnel works. Collins St is very dangerous. Close this bit of Flinders Lane (other than for delivery vehicles) to make it work well (like is done for other Little streets sometimes)!

Lots of low hanging foliage and some greenery reduces effective path width and makes sighting worse along this section. Big dropoff from the edge of the concrete along a lot of the south/west edge of this path too
comment_1: Saw a horrendous crash here in April.

description:
The most poorly maintained bike path in Australia poor lighting it floods no signage poor maintenance 
Absolutely the worst 
Which ever authority that maintains this they should get the sack
The P.S.O's at this station are complete a**holes and theyll pick on anybody with a bicyle

This is  the one of the worst intersections in Melbourne. I was hit by a car here. Bike path ends leaving cyclists and pedestrians on a small traffic Island. the area is a hot spot for hoon drivers.

spot_name: Capital City Trail Moonee Ponds Creek Trail, Melbourne Victoria
description: Love this bike path but it floods so easily!! So frustrating when you get there and have to turn back or wade through knee-deep water
comment_1: Lloyd: Totally agree with David, So frustrating when you get there and have to turn back

Bike path butts against entrances to medical center and flats with blind corners which could cause accidents for inexperienced riders. 
Path would be better if it was set back a meter or two from frontages.
Appreciate the bike easements on roads making cycling safer, hate the accumulation of debris and litter in the bike lane - would like to see the bike easements cleaned more frequently.

Cycle lane ends at intersection southbound. In either direction in Colchester, traffic overtakes cyclist within same lane and mid intersection, forcing cyclist into broken glass and other debris.
Pushy drivers, car doors and variety of cycling abilities make this entire street a nightmare.
comment_1: kg: Delivery trucks, poorly parked utes and suvs often take up some of the already small bike lane leaving little margin for error in a busy corridor. Bikes and cars are a problem here.

description: Cars do not stop at the stop sign.
comment_1: Ella: Cars do not stop at the stop sign. Turning traffic is also dangerous.

Consistent close calls with cars speeding to pass cyclists

comment_1: ben higs: Agreed, see this a lot too.

description: The bike lane here is a two-way bike lane but it's not signalled to the drivers who are turning left into Canterbury Road and many of them are surprised and don't give way to bikes crossing the intersection.
comment_1: Have had many cars not stop as i try and turn right into canterbury road from the bike lane

description: Two car lanes merge into one - cars very distracted.  Bike lane begins when car lane moves to one but cars merge into bike lane

I have seen so many accidents along here
Worst stretch in town
comment_1: David: Also poor pedestrian behaviour. I have had one pedestrian walk into the bike lane in front of me.

description: Cars fail to give way to cyclists riding down the hill through the roundabout as most traffic turns left
comment_1: Georgina Heydon: I agree with this and have experienced the same many times.

description: I have found it to be unsafe where two car lanes become one.  This occurs in both directions.  I would prefer to use the main Yarra trail, but it is not paved and the gravel makes it unsuitable for Bikes with road tyres.
comment_1: Georgina Heydon: I agree and add that the cycling lane northbound is often strewn with rocks and other debris making it unsafe.

description: Angry drivers and lack of safe bike lane
comment_1: dangerous both ways crossing Punt Rd. Often buses passing, no or no proper bike lanes. At the same time, forbidden to hop on footpath.

description: Drivers often breaking the 50 km/hr speed limit, dangerously undertaking tram, very rarely keeping 1m distance.
Two incidents in the span of a month. First a person pulling into a car spot suddenly and stopping in the bicycle lane. Second time a person turned left without indicating taking out a cyclist.
The only place to sit is in the left hand lane and the light sequence is such that cars are behind you and b continuously when the arrow is on even though this lane is also for going straight

description: Lots of speeding drivers all along this road. Very difficult at some intersections to get across road‚Äîleads to impatient and stupid behavior by drivers, esp. tradies (there‚Äôs a surprise).
comment_1: Maxum: Very poor road for cycling. Uneven surface, potholes, broken road edges. description: A lot of vehicles are not looking to give wary at this intersection
comment_1: Yes agree, I've had many near misses there.

description: Road rage drivers cause me to avoid this area, even after contacting local police several times.

description:
