comment_1: Doorzone the entire length of Koornang Rd. Needs dedicated protected bike lane and raised pedestrian crossings.

description: The consideration of other users (cyclists, motorbikes, scooters) ins't taken in here as cars go on odd angles to get into different lanes, blocking through access.

spot_name: Heidelberg - Kinglake Road, Cottles Bridge Victoria
description: Too many vehicles, moving too quickly (80km/hr limit) on Narrow winding roads, with almost no shoulder. Poor sight lines for drivers. Minimal opportunity for drivers to pass cyclists safely for 7km from Hurstbridge to St Andrews.
comment_1: cyclist: Agree. This is an extremely dangerous road for cyclists and drivers get frustrated at the lack of passing opportunity for 7km leading to aggression
comment_2: David Milella : Ye the speed limit is 80 Kph ,way too fast for the road conditions in the stretch of road from Hurstbridge to St Andrews. Most drivers do  the right thing by slowing and passing with enough space but unfortunately some don't.
comment_3: Matt: Agree, early morning only. On Saturdays you get lots of car driving south after going to the St Andrews Market. Increased bike related signage would be good.
comment_4: Ian M: Often ride this section on a Sunday morning. Wouldn't do so at other times for the reasons in prior comments
comment_5: Pete: Yes, the only safe speed along here is really 60-70 kmh. Speed limits need a review, but drivers MUST always drive to the conditions. Slow down on winding roads and be prepared to slow a lot for bicycle riders

description: Close passes (on either side of the bike lane) and tailgating happen at all the turning off lanes to Watergardens Shopping Centre, and all intersections along the Melton highway. Some drivers can't figure out if they should cross the bike lane ahead of a bike or behind it, putting the bike rider at risk. Others are simply aggressive. Happens peak and off peak.
comment_1: Steve: Debris covers the bicycle lanes both ways on the K/M Highway. Needs to be regularly swept.

description: Drivers frequently make illegal turns here, frequently and dangerously from the main road (across the service road) and cyclists at this intersection appear to be colour blind.

No bicycle lane. Moreover the cars zooming past have no respect to bike riders safety on this road. Happens everyday on my commute to and from work. This road is the only access from my place to the nearby Darebin Creek trail I use for my everyday commute.
Cars leaving the intersection never respect and always drive in the bike lane that starts here, rather than moving over, forcing bikes off the road.

Quet street which would be great, but some vehicles park illegally along here (double lines) every day and Narrow the road, such that vehicles travel on the wrong side around blind bends, which is very dangerous. Why is this parking not being patrolled?

Great sweeping bend, but many drivers (including Route 612 buses) fail to stop at the end of Erne St, and ever more vehicles are parking illegally (not 3m clearance to solid centre line) along Kinsale Cr, which forces users onto the wrong side around a blind bend risking a head-on (especially for a bike which is harder to see), coupled with the challenge of high speed cornering.
I have been cut off at least once a week by vehicles pulling in here in front of me, including a small truck.
Traffic lights need to be installed as this is an extremely dangerous intersection.
Drivers frequently miss the lights at Canning St intersection of Alexandra Parade and drive straight through on red.
comment_1: Nicole: Agree, have almost been hit by car who ran straight through a red light here.

spot_name: Path joins road at The Esplanade
description: The off-road path over the bridge ends and turns into a green-painted on-road cycle lane. Drivers here often fail to give way when turning left, sometimes accompanied by also being an illegal left turn due to the time of day.
comment_1: Martin: If you're riding a bike, you're still meant to give way to traffic on the road when entering or crossing it, even if it is a bike lane
comment_2: Martin - not sure what you mean here. Anyone (including vehicles and bikes) crossing or merging across a marked lane (including a bike lane) needs to give way to traffic in that lane (including bikes). The issue is that cars cut off cyclists by swerving across the bike lane, or pulling out in front of them - i.e. failing to give way. Cyclists aren't obliged to and shouldn't stop to let someone else cut them off

description: This is a hill climbing into Bulla from Sunbury it is 2 lanes wide the drivers refuse to pass cyclist safely often less than 1 meter, the police refuse to prosecute the drivers even with video evidence. It is time the cops did more than speeding fines and started on working to improve driver behaviour to cyclist.
Cut off frequently by drivers, have been doored by an Uber passenger here too

It seems there are many motorists who shouldn't have a licence as they do not know how to perform hook turns. I have watched so many near misses at this intersection as a result of poor hook turns from La Trobe into Exhibition. Some get angry and lean on the horn pressuring motorists in front to proceed when they are required by law to wait. As a result panicked drivers create chaos and risky turn
Heading north the lane Narrows. Drivers shift to the left and often ignores the bicycles that get pushed off the paved surface to avoid getting hit.
Taxis frequently use the wide bike lane as a place to wait for customers. The bike lane needs to be Narrowed at the entrance, or police need to enforce the rules.
comment_1:
Agreed. Here and throughout Melbourne taxis and ride-hailing drivers use bike lanes like a parking lane regardless of whether there are actual car parks available nearby or not.
Similarly, at lights, drivers use bike lanes like overtaking lanes or turning lanes well before the broken lines commence.

description: Cars regularly park in the wide spots next to the stadium and still manage to leave a wheel or sometimes more in the bicycle lane. It's dicey riding along here in morning traffic (East bound) because you have parked cars well into the bike lane and careless truck drivers zooming down Olympic Boulevard on your right. It gets very tight and it's incredibly dangerous.
Drivers are often speeding and it is hard to drive either left or right out of here to join the bicycle lane. Also onstreet parking along Harding St means visibility can be limited.
Trucks turning left across pedestrian crossing. A cyclist has been killed here

The lights at the intersection have a left turn arrow for drivers before the main green light.  Drivers bully cyclists in the bike lane to go onto the footpath or into the gutter so they can use the bike lane to turn left when there is a car going straight ahead of them.  This happens every single day at this intersection with some drivers squeezing through for a 5 sec advantage.
Cars usually stop forward of stop line at lights, and often block the crossing.  Sometimes they get stranded too far forward and reverse back through crossing or speed forward on red light.

Traffic often attempts to overtake cyclists on this blind corner. On two occasions I have been close-shaved with less than 20 cms of space given; one occasion the driver actually ran the side of his car along by elbow!

Drivers in this area are arrogant c**ts!
Speeding, high-volume and incredibly arrogant drivers on this stretch of road. Police enforcement is required but clearly absent.

Always hazardous, full of hoons and aggressive drivers. Ski-bunnies in winter, power-boat fools in summer. This road requires a 60 kmh speed limit right through to Narbethong and real police enforcement.
no bike lanes, cars doing iligal u turns, prople opering doors randomly
cars are just doing there own thing, and going where ever they want, its not a good experience, lots of risk of being dorred
drivers get really close here im not sure why there seems to be room
During peak hour, drivers often use cycle lane to pass queued vehicles to turn left on side streets or Belmore Road
Cyclists are caught between parked cars and traffic. Drivers turning left onto Queensberry St will drive into the bike lane or completely cut cyclists off, forcing them into the gutter.
Vehicles travelling east on Albert and changining lanes to turn left onto Hoddle Street cross over the bike lane, often unsafely and at speed.
comment_1: Laura: Agreed, the green bike lane runs through the middle of the onwards traffic lane and left turning lane and drivers cut across without regard for cyclists.

description: Even when you are well within the bike lane, drivers will cut the left hand corner, put half a car width into the bike lane and brush past you. Your life as a cyclist is not as important to the driver as minimising lateral cornering forces.

During school hours Wellington and surrounding streets are chock full of parents dropping children off at schools. Cyclists are treated as something to force out of the way and often end up retreating to the footpath for their safety. West of Glenferrie Road is better but dooring is a hazard. Roads should be changed to one way with permanent cycle lanes and car parks removed on one side.
comment_1: Tried this way once. Never again

description: Pedestrians often ignore signs and use cycle path instead of foot path. Drivers turning onto Wellington do not give way to cyclists. Cyclists should be given advance signal as they are at Stevenson and Denmark.

Cars regularly illegally enter and queue in the bike lane in the afternoon peak, creating a third queue at the lights, blocking bikes, and causing a snarl when they get through and all squeeze into the 2 actual lanes. Never seen any enforcement here. The lane could be better delineated too (in the wet it kinda looks like a car lane given its size and the road geometry). Head start light would help

Drivers ignore the clearway here every day. Picking up or dropping off, swapping drivers (?!), food delivery service, just plain parked etc. 

Enforce please!

Empty boat trailers here are impossible to see in the dark - no reflectors or lights, grey colour, blocking the road and entrances to the riverside area, and making it much harder for vehicles to turn.

There's no chance these are legally parked (there are No Standing signs everywhere) yet there's no enforcement. These trailers need to be stored somewhere else

Taxis stop in the clearly marked "No Standing" area because the taxi rank is full. Enforcement needed to stop the resulting constant traffic jam and hazards to bikes trying to get through. Remove the rank altogether if can't follow the rules - there's plenty of space inside the station building or shopping centre premises for a pickup area, and clearly not much demand
Cars frequently fail to give way at this intersection
Vehicles often overtake here in a dangerous fashion
comment_1: I ride this climb often. Usually traffic isn't too bad but I now avoid it on Sundays - after 9:00am its the boy-racer slot and full of blokes in fast cars they don't know how to drive...

description: Cars and particularly trucks continue to right turn into Burnley street when the right turn signal has gone red and the through traffic has a green light. Very bad when a car is closely following a truck.

When cars are stopped to turn into Nicholson street, following drivers duck into the left lane at the end of the tram stop without indicating or looking, on the assumption that nothing is using the left lane. Dangerous if you happen to be in that spot when a car swerves.

spot_name: Normanby Road, Anniversary trail crossing  Victoria
description: Shared path much used by cyclists zebra crossing with cyclist dismount signs. Normanby rd is a busy rat run and visibility for drivers as they approach the crossing is often limited by parked vehicles needs a cyclist priority raised crossing adjacent to ped' crossing with parking removed to improve site lines and speed bumps to reduce vehicle approach speeds
Taxis often pull over into car spaces on St Kilda Road and block part of the bike lane.
Drivers seem to creep across into the bike lane from here until the Domain Interchange.

There is low awareness among drivers about the purpose of bike boxes. Cars frequently stop over the bike box here, and this could be said for bike boxes all over Melbourne. There appears to be limited enforcement of stopping distance from bike boxes.
Ute completely failed to give way and pulled in front of me off Army Rd, had to slam on my brakes and skid in order to avoid running into the side of him.

Passenger cars drive over the bike path to make a "straight line" out of the round about. Even when there is a cyclist within the bike path at the time. Your life as a cyclist is not worth the extra effort to a driver to keep their vehicle within the lines.
Cars turning from Wellington on to Peel cut off cyclists in the bike lane.
comment_1: Tara: I've come inches to death SO MANY TIMES when cars turn right through gaps in the back-up traffic and then cross the bike lane that they have been unable to see

description: This track is too rough.
The bitumen path is of poor quality. The underpass of Southern Road is difficult to ride.
comment_1: Jason Hill: Agreed. Path needs resurfacing urgently.

description: Major conflict between cyclists going opposite directions and pedestrians due to Narrowing of smooth-top pathway. Everyone is jammed into one lane
comment_1: Nick: Agreed with the above.
comment_2: Yes this is major issue. Raised with the council ten years ago. No resolution
comment_3: Agreed!
comment_4: IT is not practical to hve this as a shared path. Pedestrians and bikes need to be separated.
comment_5: Steve: It's baffling to me that we're banned from using the much wider/safer paths for sharing IN the gardens.

description: The bicycle lane inexplicably stops here and you‚Äôre on the road with big trucks Then forced into the middle of the street Due to big dangerous pot holes in the left hand side of the road (towards Williamstown)

Granite speed humps make the whole area much less safe for pedestrians and cyclists. 

These speed humps are incredibly dangerous. Stop and watch one morning.  This is one of the busiest bike paths in Melbourne and the only thing they do is force the majority of bikes into the tiny flat verge, distracting them from stopping for pedestrians and greatly increasing the risk of a bike on bike/pedest
comment_1: Leroy: Vibration from granite speed humps is very distracting, even when riding slow. Also very slippery when its wet.

description: While I applaud the recent Wellington St bike line upgrades, the new bicycle stencils inside the lanes have been applied on top of previous ones, and many of them are now several layers deep which makes for a very bumpy ride. This is the case along much of Wellington St, and on both sides.
Tree roots under the shared pedestrian/bike path make this stretch very unsafe to ride on.
Very large pot holes (I think from the busses) that can easily cause aa bike accident
comment_1: Warwick Smith: HUGE HOLE. I hit it, terrifying. Survived.
comment_2: Tom: Yes and it‚Äôs the buses as it‚Äôs on their wheels spots
comment_3: Yes! It is so bad!

description: Tree roots have severely impacted surface. Unsafe to ride on bike trail with road cycle. Usually ride on street instead.
comment_1: Wayne : Better to use Ricdanic drive to access the Dandenong creek trail

description: Potholes every 10-20m right where a cyclist would ride. Results in some very bumpy spots.
comment_1: Pot holes and tree root up lifts.

description: Surface in the bus lane travelling west along Doncaster Rd, just west of the intersection with Wetherby Rd is appalling.
Road is very rough and unsafe full of potholes

I come here to shop on my bike. If you are trying to pay attention to all the cars reversing, you might miss the drains on the ground that can swallow bicycle tyres. Happened to me and I flipped over, ripping my elbow open.
comment_1: John Englart: Yes, the gratings in the carpark are a real cycle hazard, especially for thin tyres

description: As there are lots of pot holes in the bike lane and its very thin when cars drive past very fast it makes it very hard to ride your bike.
comment_1: Rod: On the east-bound side of Canterbury Rd here, the tarmac is in a dismal state of repair. There are bluestones coming out at right-angles and road plugs with sharp corners, meaning a cyclist needs to choose between navigating these or using the vehicle lane (which is generally safer).

description: The surface is very bumpy with potholes and there is so much rubbish on the hard shoulder it‚Äôs safer to ride on the road.
Poor surface, very bumpy. Not great for inexperienced riders going around bends if riding at speed

Road condition is really poor. Thin bike tires can easily get caught in the large road cracks either side of Chapel St causing accidents. It‚Äôs like getting your tyre caught in a tram track. Construction also adds slippery metal plates on the bike path often - extremely dangerous
Cracks and breaks in road surface

It would be nice to have a proper surface to ride/walk on rather than the dirt track that has been created from usage.
Its slippery in wet weather.
Potholes cracks drains
Surface is terrible and a bike lane, popular cycling route.
Large bumps across track particularly for road bikes heading north down the hill.
comment_1: Arthur: I noticed these were all marked recently with white paint so assuming these will get fixed soon....

description: The road is very un-even & rough
comment_1: Michael Rosenau: Since completion of new building on corner, the road has lots of pot holes, uneven surface, patch fixes and add traffic congestion for that corner and hang on for your life
comment_2: Damien: I have written to the council and Vic roads about the poor condition of this road many times over the years with no action.
comment_3: Marieke: Extremely poor conditions for bikes. Holes from roadworks that never get completed, man holes every few meters in the bike lane.

description: Perrins Creek rd has little traffic and is a beautiful road to ride but the surface has really disintegrated - I stick to going up it rather than down at the moment due to the poor road surface
End of bike trail is poorly surfaced around vehicle gate posts, leaving too Narrow a space for cyclists to navigate around gate posts
comment_1: MRM: There is a power poll in the middle of the path running alongside McIntyre st.

spot_name: Western Ring Road Trail, Glenroy Victoria
description: This section of the Ring Rd Trail always seems to be a collector of litter. So much crap. A clean now and then would be great.

Historic blue stone kerb is in place here which takes up 2/3 of the bike lane in the peak. not suitable for riders picking up pace as they go downhill. recommend resurfacing and utilising the historic stones as a kerb only or a new landscaping buffer along the park edge - better opportunity to appreciate these instead of just as a gutter.
comment_1: David: I agree this is very dangerous road surface, no warning and it seems to be there to discourage cyclists from what should be an important route.  From the road markings it likes this was once sealed properly but later dug up because councils and others seem to love stone paving no matter how dangerous it is.

description: Poor road surface for both cars and cyclists here between Glenferrie Road and Elizabeth Street. Potholes, poor reconstruction and limited follow up by contractors on their works in the road. This is for both directions.

spot_name: Crn Gertrude and George St  Fitzroy
description: The intersection is uneven cobblestones with a significant dip which functions as a gutter.
Please seal Ferndale Trail along its whole length. It would be a valuable alternate route
Road surface is uneven with lots of potholes on left hand side
Raised pile of concrete. Poor construction on the road. I always have to avoid it and make sure I‚Äôm not riding over it. Its harder in the morning or night when dark though.

spot_name: Chapel Street (soutbound between Alma and Argyle),  Victoria
description: It can be quite a fast downhill. With trams, cars and motorbikes a bumpy surface adds difficulty. There is also a tram stop at the bottom of the hill which is sometimes hard to brake for. Would a raised or clearer intersection at Argyle/Chapel assist?
Poor surfaces and high traffic area
Big lumps and potholes in the road
comment_1: and no bike lane!

spot_name: Eastern Freeway overpass to Stanton St
description: While having a bridge here to get across the freeway is great, the planks used on the bridge are irregular widths and make this uncomfortable and potentially dangerous to ride on.
Please seal this trail. I always use Valda Ave and cut through the carpark further north instead because this is gravel.
Road surface very uneven - large potholes, drain grates and depressions.
joins in the concrete a major hazzard
Coming down hill at speed with a transition from gravel to concrete on an off camber bend after a run off bar. Needs a berm.

Drivers often pull out with out looking / indicating. The road condition is poor in that the tram line foundation and road are distinctly different heights. So it is difficult ride at a cautious distance from parked cars.
Perfect Fed trail on one side of bridge, perfect Werribee river trail otherside and totally unsealed goats track under the Freeway.....I mean, you only had one job!

This bridge is old, Narrow and rickety.  It is a popular route for cyclists however cyclists are supposed to dismount at the bridge which is annoying for cyclists.  Very few do this (including myself if the bridge is empty) and there can be conflict with pedestrians.  This bridge should be upgraded so cyclists can cycle across it while keeping pedestrians safe.
comment_1: Agree - many cyclists put up with the rough surface and ride accross this bridge - ignoring the "cyclists dismount" signs.   This is a logical safe route from Fairfield to and from the Boulevard and it needs appropriate cycling infrastructure to cross the river from Yarra Bend.
comment_2: Tara: Agree, we need to have a bicycle friendly bridge!

description: Popular area with Kew Rec and Coles.  The road is very bumpy going from Parkhill into Derby Place.  Derby Place very Narrow and no clear route if you are cycling to Kew Rec.
This is a great safe alternative to riding up the Windy Mile however the loose gravel and rock boulders are difficult to navigate. Widening the rock boulders slightly and a more compacted surface.

This has been fixed up a bit, but it could be so much better to encourage people to cycle to the station, the Uni, the new school campus (Under construction). Needs pram crossings, clear indication of cycle / pedestrian zones, and being able to ride over the overpass would help instead of "cyclists dismount"
This part of the road is getting more and more uneven by the day, nothing is done about it
Speed bumps are too aggressive for cycling over. Creates safety risk and uncomfortable for rider

What be nice if accessing this lane was easier. Tricky to get to when going downhill to the river as under pressure from cars flying down the hill and even though curb is lowered it‚Äôs still a bit hand in mouth
Several square patches of bumpy asphalt in a row, takes up the bike lane
comment_1: You either have to move in close to parked cars to dodge it (never safe), or move into the traffic.

description: The path has occasional breaks where the trail is paved with bluestone bricks - very beautiful but also a very poor bumpy surface to cycle over. (I imagine this also has accessibility issues.) Putting in a Narrow ashpalted line across the bricks would allow cyclists to travel unimpeded, while still maintaining the aesthetic value of the bricks.

Long interruption in the path with bluestone bricks. Very bumpy ride. The bricks are beautiful but some sort of Narrow asphalted lane across the bricks would allow bikes (and other wheeled users) to travel unimpeded.
There's a big pothole somewhere in the vicinity of here, I've hit it a few times when coming downhill in the dark, can be very dangerous.

spot_name: Kings Way On Ramp, Melbourne Victoria
description: The road surface here is terrible and has been that way for years.  Even more dangerous in low light conditions.
This road requires sealing to be safe for the cyclists, walkers, runners & horseriders who use it.

There should be a paved link between the Main Yarra Trail in Westerfolds Park and the Diamond Creek Trail at the bridge over the Yarra. This is a key cycle commuting route but is dangerous in the dark and/or wet.
The path is very Narrow, badly maintained, has multiple blind corners and overhanging vegetation at several points. Council needs to give some attention to this route.

spot_name: Oxley - Greta West Road, Wangaratta Victoria
description: I love riding from Greta to Oxley but the track is a bit of a mess, plenty of potholes and with the amount of cars that drive along the road it's incredibly dusty. It can be very unsafe with cars driving along the rode as at times it's hard to get of the track with a bike.
This track has a lit of potholes and the side road plants are out of control so theres no way to walk or ride of the main track. When a car comes it is difficult to get of the track.

This road is very Narrow and for the most part doesn't have lanes marked. The road has so many potholes and is just a very uneven surface.  The side of the road can be just a ditch at some parts so getting of the road can be dangerous.

Steep and needles trail diversion to a footpath. A great discouragement for trail users. All forced upon riders by the theft of the railway easement by the Mt Lilydale College. It is well and truly time that their lease of public land was ceased and the trail re-aligned along the original *public-owned* railway line route.

This is a brutal, dangerous section of road due to the bad surface. Has been in this state for 15+ years. VicRoads is the responsible authority. 
Please create new spots all along this road from Banksia St to the Town Hall
Cycle path is very rough due to the tree roots lifting the cycle path.  It needs to be re-surfaced.

Swampy bog-hole on the Dandenong Creek Trail. After any heavy rain the path becomes a flooded gutter and stays that way for a few days. Pedestrians and bicycle riders are forced to dodge about looking for a way through. Been this state for decades now. 

Lousy stretch of trail. Well and truly time a better drained surface was constructed.
comment_1: James: Agree, This section floods badly after rain.  The drainage could easily be improved to getthe water to flow away

description: just lots of pot holes last time i rode.
theres lots of bumps and stuff to get tires stuck in, dosnt help what the bike lane disappear sat all the intersections when we actually need it.

Very good off-road shared path from Wangaratta to Milawa for casual riders but surface is not suitable for road bikes.   Snow Road particularly is Narrow with no shoulders.   Existing path should be upgraded to a hotmix style finish to encourage use by road based cyclists.   On road cyclist fatality along this stretch a few years ago despite the adjoining offroad bike path.
Very Poor surface but also very Narrow when turning. It also needs a mirror or something so you can see anyone coming from around the corner.
Un-level/bumpy surface makes for very rough ride

There is a drain at the west end of the underpass that is extremely slick when wet but is also very hard to avoid when riding westbound since you can't see it until just before you reach it. I've crashed due to this drain and suspect I'm not the only one.
No bike lanes forces you into a really rough shoulder with high levels of traffic. Makes for a really unpleasant ride eastbound
There is often a large amount of sediment and debris on the path here from overflow following rain.
Drainage issues in the westbound bike lane and then left lane from Officeworks to Burnley St. Rest of the westbound road is mostly fine for drainage (obviously under the same weather condition)
Huge bumps in road. No bike lane. Trucks speeding past.

spot_name: Box Hill to Ringwood Rail Trail,  Victoria
description: There is a gap in the tarmac here, and a weird diversion around some rail(?) infrastructure

Poor street lighting mixed with poor repairs to ever increasing potholes, mixed with large gravel strewn over cycle zone creates a dangerous mix
for road bikes with Narrower wheels , even though i know its there I've almost lost it 3 times
Road surface is terrible on most of this street
Much debris in bicycle lanes and many pot holes along length of Cheltenham Rd.
The road surface here is beginning to deteriorate and construction barriers/hoarding encroaches on the bike lane and bike box at the intersection.
There is large hole running perpendicular to the road here.

It is great to have this side ramp up the steps for cyclists who can't lift their bikes up stairs but the asphalt type surface on top of the metal has worn away and when it is wet the bike slides alot when trying to push it up the ramp (I also have many kilos of produce from vic market in my paniers which makes it more difficult to get up a slippery wet metal surface) please reapply the surface :)
Bike track in desperate need of repair from kurunjang wall the way to Melton south
Terrible surface, not appealing to anything other than bmx's, so a missed opportunity to reduce traffic again.
With no bike lane and a high volume of traffic, riding on the road feels fairly vulnerable here.

spot_name: North of Nicholson And Holden St Intersection
description: Two lanes of road traffic try to merge into one as the head north on Nicholson St and often don‚Äôt leave enough space or get frustrated by riders.

We need to connect the bike path from Fairfield park through to the Alphington bike path and avoid roads all together.

I commute daily to work and also ride with the family on weekends and the city circle bike path and Yarra trail are fantastic but we need to ensure connection and not have gaps where bike riders need to go on roads.
If we had full connection more commuters would ride
Cars use Latham St and Beavers Road as a rat run. Too much traffic and disregard for speed limits.
Narrow bike lane, too much traffic, dangerous intersection
comment_1: Major entry to city, terribly dangerous intersection with mixture of cars and bikes.
comment_2: Bike lane gets really Narrow at this intersection. This, coupled with the strange driver propensity to veer to the right into the bike lane before turning left, makes this intersection really dangerous.
comment_3: Jackie: Bikelane Narrow...very, very Narrow...and between two lanes of cars. Cars straddle the bike lane and also swing out into it as they turn left making it particularly dangerous.
comment_4: ClareB: This is the closest I come to death on a daily basis. Bike lane Narrows to width of a single bike on a car-choked thoroughfare plus buses. Raised markers along bike lane tend to 'turn' Narrow tyres.
comment_5: Hui-chang: Agree the bike lane here becomes very Narrow and you end up being sandwiched between the traffic turning left and going straight, with no protection on either side.
comment_6: Chuck Kolyvas: The bike lane Narrows to less than a metre in width, leaving the cyclist wedged between heavily stacked left and forward lanes for about 30-40m before the intersection. Cars turning left often sit over the bike lane and often cut in front of cyclists hoping to catch a green arrow. The worst part is, this is the best option for entry to the CBD from Canning Street

spot_name: Exhiberg and Malthouse Lane, Melbourne Victoria
description: Cars get backed up into the cycle lane while they are waiting to get into the car park or they block the cycling lane by parking illegally for deliveries or drop offs
The PT buses and cars block the cycle lane, and turning left bus use the lane.
Busy intersection with lots of traffic. With a big supermarket nearby lots of impatient and distracted drivers.
comment_1: Jack: This is a nightmare for drivers as well! But yes very scary on a bike, given there are a bunch of bike lanes around here.
comment_2: Chris: I‚Äôll second that!!!!
comment_3: John Englart: Lizzie Blandthorn announced April 19th that work had started converting this round about to traffic lights. No details on what cycling/pedestrian infrastructure will be incorporated in new intersection
comment_4: Astir77: What happens to the Sussex St bike lane here heading north? It just disappears and a left turn lane appears. If you want to cycle straight on you have to merge out right across left merging traffic.
comment_5:
Matt Wilson: Frightening roundabout as there are two vehicle lanes on most approaches, so you have to merge across traffic in a bike on approach to a busy intersection
.

description: This road is used to commute to Mitcham station, both to and from the Park road direction, It can get very busy. There are no viable direct alternative routes. footpath riding is required as it gets so congested during the afternoon. The bike path around Mallauna college/Mitcham primary school only runs for 50m
comment_1: Pete: What bike path? There is none.

description: extremely busy road used by drivers to travel east/west
comment_1: This spot is very dangerous for cyclists heading west, as it‚Äôs a slow steep climb through a sharp left bend; a blind corner for motor vehicles heading in the same direction. Then again, there are really no blind corners, just drivers driving faster than they can see.

description: Very busy and vehicles travelling fairly quickly make travelling from North Rd to Melbourne Rd northbound can be very challenging
Bike path has to cross very busy 4 lane road. Difficult/unsafe during busy times.
comment_1: Dan: +1 No safe way across to Cherry lake and the path on the other side is just gravelly stone and unmaintained.

description: There are literally five (5) parking spots here which essentially undermine most of the gains from the full-time bus lane along the entire rest of Victoria Parade, and cause massive bottlenecks way back up the hill while buses merge into other traffic. This happens any time outside peak (4-7.30pm M-F it's no standing), so essentially the lane is always blocked and unsafe leading up to here.
Cars drive really fast through here and traffic gets heavy in peak times. As cars park on the sides it means there is less room and visibility. I have to turn right and it's really scary doing so

Turning right onto Swan Street from Stewart Street is near impossible with heavy traffic and trams. This is not a safe place to turn and people instead gamble going the other way via Punt Road along the footpath (also unsafe) to avoid this intersection.
Cars parked, heavy traffic most times, and Poor driver behaviour.
Many trucks entering or turning onto from Banksia St
The Cycle lane ends just as the road Narrows.
Take your life in your hands if you ride a bike anywhere along warrigal road

During peak hours, this intersection for cars becomes backed up with cars trying to turn right onto Hoddle Street.
